<div type="definition">

    <p resp="#CH" modified="2021-03-18T18:27:39.797+09:00">RESPONSIBILITY FOR ONE'S AVOIDABLE PAST BAD ACT. </p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The dominant standard general word for any kind of guilt, large or small, is zuì 罪 (ant. gōng 功 "merit"), but this does not refer to any feelings of guilt; the general term for feelings of guilt is jiù 疚 REGRET.</p>
<p>2. Qiān 愆, (sometimes written qiān 騫 ) refers to slight guilt or responsibility for a mistake.</p>
<p>3. Yóu 尤 refers to the blame one suffers for a misdeed.</p>
<p>For zéi 賊, a dramatic derogatory term referring to abject villainy, see VILLAIN.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>罪感 translates the Western notion of guilt.</p>
<p>犯罪感 is an expanded and perhaps slightly more common translation.</p>
<p>rough draft to BEGIN TO identify synonym group members for analysis, based on CL etc. 18.11.2003. CH ／</p>
        </div>
